Fragmentation Analysis: In the basic example, what is the external fragmentation percentage? 
Explain why free memory becomes fragmented.
      External fragmentation is 24.41%
      It fragments because processes require different amounts of memory and run for different 
      durations. When a process finishes and releases its memory, it leaves a "hole". If the
      next requesting process doesn't fit the hole perfectly, a smaller leftover hole is created.
      Over time, memory breaks down into many isolated free blocks.


First-Fit Efficiency: Why does P4 use the block left by P1 even though it's larger than needed? 
What happens to the unused portion?
      First-Fit scans memory starting from address 0 and stops at the very first block that 
      is greater than or equal to the requested size. It doesn't care if there's a better fit 
      further down.
      The unused 50 KB portion is split off into a brand-new free block. This small block 
      contributes to fragmentation since it is often too small to host future processes.

Allocation Patterns: Compare workload1.txt (many small processes) with workload2.txt (few large processes). 
Which creates more fragmentation? Why?
      workload1.txt will create significantly more fragmentation.
      Constantly carving up memory into small chunks and releasing them irregularly turns the memory
      space into a patchwork of tiny allocated blocks separated by tiny free blocks (the "swiss cheese" 
      effect). Large, infrequent processes tend to keep memory clustered in larger, contiguous chunks.

Failed Allocations: Create a scenario where an allocation fails even though the total free memory is larger than the request. 
Why does this happen?
      Total memory is 1000 KB. Processes A, B, C, D, and E (200 KB each) are allocated back-to-back. 
      Processes B and D finish, releasing their blocks. You now have 400 KB of total free memory.
      If Process F requests 300 KB, the allocation will fail. Even though there is 400 KB of total 
      free memory, it is split into two non-contiguous 200 KB blocks. Memory allocation requires a 
      single contiguous block of space.

Algorithm Comparison: How might Best-Fit allocation handle the basic example differently than First-Fit? 
Would it reduce fragmentation?
      Instead of grabbing the first available block, Best-Fit scans the entire memory array to find 
      the smallest possible free block that is >= the requested size.
      In the short term, it would reduce fragmentation. Best-Fit preserves larger contiguous blocks of memory by utilizing 
      tighter spaces first. However, long term, Best-Fit can actually generate a high volume of 
      extremely tiny leftover fragments, meaning it's not a silver bullet for external fragmentation.
